Revision history for Algorithm-Classifier-IsolationForest

0.6.0   2026-07-08/02:00
        - Implement Online Isolation Forest (Leveni, Weigert Cassales,
          Pfahringer, Bifet & Boracchi 2024, ICML, PMLR 235) as the new
          companion class Algorithm::Classifier::IsolationForest::Online.
          Streaming operation instead of fit(): points are learned as
          they arrive and forgotten once they age out of a sliding
          window, so the model tracks drift. Trees store counts and
          bounding boxes rather than points; leaves split by simulating
          points inside their box and forgetting collapses
          under-populated subtrees. Supports prequential score_learn,
          contamination thresholds relearnable from the window, tagged
          rows, and JSON persistence that keeps the window so a reloaded
          model resumes the stream.
        - Online batch scoring (score_samples, predict, path_lengths,
          score_predict_samples, score_predict_split, and the
          contamination threshold relearning built on them) runs through
          the existing Inline::C/OpenMP backend: online trees are
          axis-only, so they pack into the batch scorer's node layout
          with the online depth-budget adjustment riding in the leaf
          slot the batch packer uses for c(size) -- no new C code. The
          packed snapshot is built lazily and dropped on any learn;
          results are bit-identical to the pure-Perl fallback (use_c /
          use_openmp knobs match the parent's semantics). Measured ~60x
          single-threaded and 250x+ with OpenMP at 100 trees x 1000+
          query points; ~17x even when every scoring call follows a
          learned point and pays the repack. New benchmark script
          benchmarking/bench-online-score-accel.pl.
        - Online learning is C-accelerated too: online_learn_row_xs /
          online_unlearn_row_xs run the per-tree insert/forget walks
          (count/box bookkeeping, box-sampled leaf splits, subtree
          collapse) directly against the live Perl tree structures, and
          online_score_row_xs walks them for score_learn's per-row
          scoring. Random draws go through Drand01() in exactly the
          order the pure-Perl path calls rand(), so learn() with a
          given seed builds BIT-IDENTICAL trees whether use_c is on or
          off (nvsize == 8 perls; the depth-budget log base is pinned
          to an exact-double literal on both sides so platform libm
          rounding cannot flip a split decision). Measured ~9-10x: a
          default 100-tree model learns ~2,600 pts/s vs ~290 pure Perl,
          and score_learn / score_learn_tagged stream at ~2,800 pts/s
          vs ~270. A prebuilt C object from an older release lacks the
          new functions; the online class detects that at load and
          keeps learning in pure Perl (batch scoring stays accelerated)
          until the module is rebuilt. The accel benchmark script grew
          score_learn and score_learn_tagged sections.
        - New `iforest stream` subcommand: creates or resumes an online
          model, streams CSV rows through it (prequential by default,
          --learn-only / --score-only variants), and saves the updated
          state back.
        - `iforest info` and the parent class's load()/from_json()
          recognise online models via their stored format tag.
        - Optional Algorithm::ToNumberMunger integration for tagged data,
          on both the batch and online classes: new(mungers => {...})
          takes a declarative spec (requires feature_names; compiled and
          validated at construction) and every tagged row -- the
          *_tagged methods, the new fit_tagged(), and learn_tagged's new
          arrayref batch form -- is munged from raw values (strings,
          timestamps, status codes, ...) into numbers through the
          compiled plan. Expanding (into) and combining (from lists)
          mungers are supported via the tagged methods; the new
          munge_rows() applies scalar mungers to positional rows. The
          spec is SAVED WITH THE MODEL (plus munger_module_version), so
          a loaded model munges scoring input exactly as it did training
          input; loading a munger-bearing model does not require the
          module -- the plan recompiles lazily on first tagged use and
          croaks with an install hint if it is absent. CLI: fit and
          stream grow --mungers (JSON spec file, requires -t; munged CSV
          columns may hold raw values, re-validated numeric after
          munging), predict/stream munge raw CSV automatically when the
          model carries a spec (packed input is never munged), and info
          shows a per-tag munger summary. Algorithm::ToNumberMunger is
          a recommends, not a requirement.
        - Prototype support: a prototype is a small JSON document
          describing what a model should be before any data exists --
          the variable schema (feature_names in column order, plus
          munger specs, per-feature descriptions, and missing policy),
          a required user-owned schema_version string and free-text
          schema_description, and optionally the per-class tuning knobs
          (unknown or machine-local knobs croak). Creating a model from
          one stamps the schema metadata into the model JSON. New class
          methods new_from_prototype()/load_prototype() (single entry
          point, dispatching to batch or online by the prototype's
          class field; %overrides merge over params, the schema may not
          be overridden), validate_prototype() (structural, no munger
          compilation), and to_prototype() on both classes to extract a
          prototype back out of a model -- the retrain loop. Both
          new()s also take schema_version / schema_description /
          feature_descriptions directly (described features must exist
          in feature_names), with accessors, all persisted. CLI: fit
          and stream grow --prototype (schema comes only from the
          prototype -- combining it with -t/--mungers is refused;
          explicit tuning switches override the prototype's params),
          info shows schema_version/schema_description and prints each
          feature's description beside its tag, and the new `iforest
          proto` subcommand extracts (--from-model) and validates
          (--check) prototype files. See PROTOTYPES in the module POD
          for the file format.
        - `iforest fit` now actually passes -d through as max_depth
          (previously accepted and silently ignored).
        - New `iforest streamd` subcommand: a prequential scoring daemon
          around an online model. Listens on a Unix domain socket
          (--socket, default /var/run/iforest_streamd/streamd.sock; pid
          at --pid, default /var/run/iforest_streamd/streamd.pid),
          handles many concurrent connections in one process (a
          select loop -- rows apply to the shared model in line-arrival
          order, which defines the stream order), and speaks one JSON
          document per line via JSON::MaybeXS (new hard prereq;
          pure-Perl JSON::PP fallback), so raw values headed for
          mungers may safely carry commas, newlines, or any unicode.
          Requests take one of "row" (array = positional, object = a
          tagged row through the full munger plan, expanding/combining
          mungers included), "rows" (batch), or "cmd" (ping / stats /
          mode / save / relearn-threshold), plus an optional "mode"
          (prequential/learn/score, also settable per connection) and
          an optional client tag echoed back verbatim in the reply --
          on errors too, which are per-message and never kill the
          connection or daemon. Models save to --model-dir (default
          /var/db/iforest_streamd) as timestamped files every
          --save-interval seconds (when learning happened), on the
          save command, SIGUSR1, and shutdown, with the symlink
          latest.json atomically repointed at each save and resumed
          from at startup -- a restart loses at most one interval.
          --keep N prunes old saves; --prototype/-t/--mungers and the
          stream creation knobs cover new-model creation; SIGHUP
          reopens the log; missing state directories are created at
          startup or refused loudly before daemonizing; over-long
          socket paths (the ~104-byte sun_path limit) are refused
          instead of silently truncated. New benchmark script
          benchmarking/bench-streamd.pl measures the daemon end to end
          (spawns its own): batched rows over the socket run within
          ~2% of in-process score_learn (~2,700 vs ~2,770 pts/s at 100
          trees / 5 features on the dev box), throughput is flat
          across concurrent clients by design, and ping floors at
          ~29k round trips/s -- the model, not the wire, is the
          bottleneck. --set NAME runs a named
          instance: the set name is appended to --model-dir (its own
          saves, latest.json, resume state, and default log) and the
          socket/pid become <set>.sock / <set>.pid under the run dir
          (with --set, --socket and --pid name the base run dir instead
          of the files), so several sets run side by side with no other
          flags; set names must match /\A[A-Za-z0-9+\-@_]+\z/, whose
          class has no '.' or '/', so a name can only ever create one
          path segment. stats reports the set and the startup log line
          carries it. New test t/91-streamd.t drives live daemons over
          the socket, including two sets side by side.
        - New `iforest streamc` subcommand: the client for streamd.
          Stream mode (-i, - for stdin) feeds rows through the daemon
          in --batch sized lockstep messages and prints one result per
          row in order -- CSV input (positional rows, numeric-looking
          fields sent as numbers, everything else as raw strings for
          the daemon's munger plan) emits stream-compatible
          `$score,$label` lines with -d prepending the input columns;
          --jsonl input takes one JSON row per line (array positional,
          object tagged through the full munger plan) and emits the
          daemon's reply lines verbatim. --mode
          prequential/learn/score; row validation is entirely the
          daemon's, and both client- and daemon-side errors die naming
          the input line (requests are tagged with their starting line
          number to map batch errors back). Command mode sends --ping,
          --stats, --save, or --relearn-threshold, rendered as text or
          raw with --json, exiting 0 on ok and non-zero on error,
          connect failure, or --timeout -- so `streamc --set web
          --ping` slots straight into health checks. --set/--socket
          resolve the socket exactly as streamd does. New test
          t/92-streamc.t drives the real CLI against a live daemon.
        - New cross-language test t/80-sklearn-comparison-online.t
          (skipped without Python/scikit-learn): streams datasets of 2
          to 20 features through the online model and verifies its
          scores approach and match sklearn's batch IsolationForest --
          anomaly top-8 agreement and score-gap checks at every
          dimensionality, plus Spearman rank-correlation convergence
          checkpoints where the algorithm's box-sampling resolution
          permits (the achievable full-ranking correlation ceiling
          falls with n_features by design; measured calibration tables
          are in the test's header comment).

0.5.0   2026-07-04/14:30
        - Wide-NV perls (-Duselongdouble / -Dusequadmath(maybe? does this
          even exist? but possibly some idiot on github... but would fix
          it in this case as well): the pure-Perl tree builder now rounds
          every value it stores (split points, hyperplane coefficients and
          offsets, impute fills) to C double precision at the same points
          the C builder rounds preserving the seed-for-seed bit-identical
          guarantee across backends. Possible breakages for the tests for
          extended mode where -Duselongdouble is in play may exist so tests
          for those systems where it is are skipped for now.
        - Implement Majority Voting Isolation Forest (MVIForest --
          Chabchoub, Togbe, Boly & Chiky 2022, IEEE Access,
          doi:10.1109/ACCESS.2022.3144425) as new(voting => 'majority'):
          Since this only affects how the trees are walked etc and not build,
          the voting method can be switched between majority and mean.
         - adjust how iforest info displays tag info

0.4.0   2026-07-03/22:45
        - Implement named features and methods for testing single rows using
          tagged data.
        - The C backend can be built and installed at install time, meaning
          nothing needs built unless changing the opts. See the docs for
          more details.
        - new IF_NO_OPENMP=1 selects/builds the serial C backend: no
          libgomp linkage and no OpenMP runtime in the process at all
          (unlike OMP_NUM_THREADS=1, which just caps the thread count);
          IF_NO_OPENMP=0 re-enables OpenMP over a serial install default
        - new IF_RUNTIME_BUILD=1 ignores the prebuilt object and forces
          the classic runtime build even when the flags match
        - iforest accel updated to reflect various changes to the C backend
        - scoring: the per-leaf path-length adjustment c(size) is now
          precomputed at tree-pack time and stored in the (previously
          unused) third slot of packed leaf records, removing a log()
          call per point per tree from the C scoring hot loop -- about
          25% faster axis-mode scoring; results are bit-identical
        - scoring: score_all_xs now picks between two loop shapes based
          on total forest size: small forests keep the point-major loop
          (whole forest stays cache-resident anyway), while forests
          over 4 MB switch to a tree-blocked loop that walks a block of
          points through one tree at a time so each tree stays hot in
          L1/L2 instead of being re-streamed from memory per point --
          measured ~3.2x faster extended-mode scoring at 400 trees
          (20k points, 16 features); both shapes add the same terms in
          the same order, so scores are bit-identical either way
        - any -march (IF_ARCH / IF_NATIVE, configure- or run-time) now
          automatically adds -ffp-contract=off: with FMA available the
          compiler otherwise contracts a*b+c into fused multiply-adds
          whose different rounding silently broke the use_c bit-parity
          guarantee (one ulp in a split value builds a different tree);
          the -march win comes from vectorization, so this costs ~nothing
        - scoring: oblique nodes now prefetch both child records before
          the dot product resolves which branch is taken, hiding the
          next node's memory latency under the FMA work (~7-10% faster
          extended-mode scoring on top of the tiling; axis path is
          untouched -- its single compare has no work to hide a
          prefetch under); purely a hint, results unchanged

0.3.0   2026-07-02/23:00
        - lots of POD fixes/cleanup
        - various further C optmizations
        - fit() can now handle training data with missing (undef) feature
          cells, selectable via the new `missing =>` constructor option:
            die    :: croak on undef in the training data (default)
            zero   :: treat a missing cell as the value 0
            impute :: fill with the per-feature mean/median (see `impute_with`)
            nan    :: range over present values and route missing rows to the
                      right child, consistently at fit and score time
        - new `impute_with => 'mean'|'median'` option for impute mode ...
          missing strategy + impute fill vector are persisted in saved models;
          models from older releases load as `zero` (the prior undef -> 0
          scoring behaviour)
        - the C build is now tunable via environment variables read at first
          module load: IF_ARCH=<value> adds -march=<value>, IF_NATIVE=1 is
          shorthand for IF_ARCH=native, IF_OPT overrides the default -O3,
          and IF_NO_C=1 skips building the C backend entirely; values are
          validated (bad ones warn and fall back to the defaults) and the
          flags actually used are exposed via $OPT_LEVEL
        - Benchmarking: bench-sklearn-scoring.pl now compares pure Perl, C,
          and C+OpenMP fit/score paths against sklearn side by side

0.2.1   2026-06-30/14:30
        - derp... actually update MANIFEST so a bunch of files from last release
          are actually included

0.2.0   2026-06-30/14:15
        - C acceleration via Inline::C for core fit and predict ops
        - OpenMP support for parallel multi-threaded fitting and predict ops
        - SIMD (AVX/SSE) acceleration where available
        - Data packing support for compact model storage (new `pack` CLI command)
        - Parallel fit capability
        - New `score_predict_split` method
        - New `accel` CLI command for querying available acceleration flags
        - New `bench` CLI command for running built-in benchmarks
        - New `info` CLI command with expanded model introspection
        - Benchmarking scripts covering fit, predict, scoring, and accel modes
        - Tests: accel flag detection, accel selection, undef column handling,
          data packing, parallel fit, sklearn comparison (including undef),
          and CLI
        - minor tweaks to `csv2plot` for a bit nicer rendering
        - minor POD fixes

0.1.0   2026-06-23/03:15
        - add csv2plot helper command for graphing

0.0.1   2026-06-21/21:45
